[04:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'and it took a really long time. And now H higher&nbsp; is basically doing that automatically for you&nbsp;&nbsp; which is of course really amazing. So what you&nbsp; could do now once you\'re happy with it is that&nbsp;&nbsp; you can then go inside the connector settings. So&nbsp; you could choose here the connector type that you&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'would like to have for example the default one&nbsp; the ball one or the do detail one. I\'m having&nbsp;&nbsp; right now as you can see here the do of detail&nbsp; which is basically the standard one I would say.&nbsp;&nbsp; and say here generate connector and then once&nbsp; done you can see this is then basically how&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'the connectors look like with the regenerated&nbsp; mode. And this of course really cool because you&nbsp;&nbsp; can change them quite easily by just adding here&nbsp; basically the connectors you would like to have.&nbsp;&nbsp; And this is not it because when we go back here&nbsp; into our merge view you will actually see that we&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'have for example here a crashing connector that&nbsp; is going through and obviously we would like to&nbsp;&nbsp; avoid that before printing. So what you can do&nbsp; is of course that you also go to the advanced&nbsp;&nbsp; connector settings that we have here. And once we&nbsp; are in here you will see on the right side that we&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'have here connection points. And this is really&nbsp; nice because this gives us even more control to&nbsp;&nbsp; basically then control our connectors. So what&nbsp; we can do is first saying something like add all&nbsp;&nbsp; connectors. Then it will give us a preview of the&nbsp; connectors it would like to generate. We can then&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'for example adjust then the scale of it. So we can&nbsp; say what kind of scale it should have. And it will&nbsp;&nbsp; also give us then a preview here like how it will&nbsp; look in the end before connecting it so that we&nbsp;&nbsp; can avoid exactly that issue that I just showed&nbsp; you that it\'s not crashing anymore. So basically&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'something like this I think could already work.&nbsp; You could also change the assembly fit so that&nbsp;&nbsp; it\'s evenly spread out across the connectors. So&nbsp; this will then basically say if you would like&nbsp;&nbsp; to have the connectors more loose or more tight.&nbsp; So a loose gives you of course more flexibility&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'and more smoother motion while the smaller is&nbsp; a tight fit overall. And you can also read it&nbsp;&nbsp; here in detail basically what is recommended. So&nbsp; you can see it\'s kind of small value and you can&nbsp;&nbsp; then see what works best for you. And we even&nbsp; have your connection length which is of course&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'also very useful because as you can see you can&nbsp; then change here how far you would like to have&nbsp;&nbsp; it. What I also noticed here is by the way that&nbsp; you know when you change here to another mode,&nbsp;&nbsp; it\'s way faster than when you would do it outside&nbsp; of this menu. And once you are then kind of happy&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'with the connectors you have here, you can&nbsp; then click here on generate connector and&nbsp;&nbsp; then it will generate that for us. And this would&nbsp; then take some time. But since we had that really&nbsp;&nbsp; nice preview already, we can then be sure that&nbsp; our connectors are working for us. By the way,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'generally speaking about the different connectors&nbsp; that we have here, I would recommend you to use&nbsp;&nbsp; the ball connector if you would like to move the&nbsp; parts around once you printed them so that you&nbsp;&nbsp; can, for example, move the arm up and down and so&nbsp; on. For the pinning connector that we have here,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'this is basically when you would like just to&nbsp; move your model in only one axis. And for the&nbsp;&nbsp; last connector that I used here, the dove detail,&nbsp; this one is a traditional plug-in connector&nbsp;&nbsp; that you might have seen already on a lot of 3D&nbsp; printed models. And this one is just there that&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'once assembled you can\'t move it. But I think&nbsp; I still prefer it because most times I really&nbsp;&nbsp; would just like to have it standing on my desk&nbsp; for example. So I don\'t really need to move it. And I also wanted to show you quickly that the&nbsp; split feature is not only for characters. Of&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[08:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'course, you can obviously also print hard surface&nbsp; assets, weapons, and props, which is also really&nbsp;&nbsp; cool because I did it here as an example on this&nbsp; crossbow that I prompted also with nano banana.&nbsp;&nbsp; Once I had this, I can then also go to the image&nbsp; to 3D. Then I can generate the mesh here. By the&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[08:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'way, he mentioned as well that all the meshes you&nbsp; generate are watertight. So you can directly then&nbsp;&nbsp; feed them into your 3D slicer and import them and&nbsp; then print them from there, which is of course&nbsp;&nbsp; very really handy that we don\'t need to fix it&nbsp; for example in Blender. So once we have that here,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[08:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'same settings basically that I used before. We can&nbsp; then hit here generate. And then once generated,&nbsp;&nbsp; you will see that we get this really nice detailed&nbsp; model over here of our crossbow with all the&nbsp;&nbsp; different parts that we need. And now of course&nbsp; you might guess it, we would like to split this&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[08:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'as well. So you can then choose again the split&nbsp; parts feature on the bottom. And then what we&nbsp;&nbsp; going to do and this is the main difference is&nbsp; that we then go instead of character to general&nbsp;&nbsp; on the top right. You can then choose between&nbsp; the split mode and professional mode. Most of&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[09:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'the times I\'m using then the professional mode&nbsp; because here we can then find the best angle to&nbsp;&nbsp; split our model. So we make it basically for the&nbsp; AI easier to recognize our model. And you will&nbsp;&nbsp; see some great examples also on the left side.&nbsp; You can then choose an angle here like I did&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[09:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'with the crossbow. So all the parts are clearly&nbsp; visible kind of and that it\'s clearly readable.&nbsp;&nbsp; And then once you have your pose ready, I then hit&nbsp; confirm. And then we can also already choose our&nbsp;&nbsp; segmentation detail level for here. I think medium&nbsp; is way more than enough. And then once generated,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[09:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'you will see that it first gives us here a mask.&nbsp; And you can also see that we now can basically&nbsp;&nbsp; edit this mask. So the kind of rendered image&nbsp; that we have here, which is kind of a normal&nbsp;&nbsp; presentation. And from there it draws then the&nbsp; masks that will be used then for splitting. So&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[09:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
